00:36.380 --> 00:38.120
And here are your hosts.

00:42.540 --> 00:50.880
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Of all the themes handled by science fiction
authors, that of alien contact has been one of the most consistently popular and

00:50.880 --> 00:58.420
fascinating. For a good reason, too. Aliens, whether they be the hostile bug
-eyed monsters of the old pulp magazines or the friendly creatures of close

00:58.420 --> 01:06.080
encounters of the third kind, have always been one of the biggest attractions of
science fiction. In the past, stories of alien contact were usually written as

01:06.080 --> 01:15.380
thrillers, with the sole and simple intention of scaring readers. H.G. Wells'
The War of the Worlds is probably the best example of that type of story. But

01:15.380 --> 01:22.960
that's changed. Many contemporary writers have provided more thoughtful
treatments of aliens, deepening the realism and the significance of narratives

01:22.960 --> 01:23.920
of alien contact.

01:32.000 --> 01:40.380
Of course, before you can have a story of alien contact, you have to have some
aliens. One of the most provocative descriptions of aliens in all of science

01:40.380 --> 01:49.160
fiction is found in Larry Niven's and Jerry Pournelle's The Mote in God's Eye. The
success of that book is largely due to the unique and ingenious aliens, the

01:49.160 --> 01:57.220
Moties, that Niven created for the story. It's interesting, though, that Niven
says he doesn't really create aliens for a story, but suggests that it's the

01:57.220 --> 02:12.060
other way around. I always design aliens for themselves. I almost never design
an alien to match a story. The story, some story will eventually include the

02:12.060 --> 02:20.820
alien. The alien stands for himself. There are two particularly fascinating
things that Niven incorporated into these Moties. One is the fact that they are

02:20.820 --> 02:29.240
not symmetrical. They have a head, torso, legs, and arms, as humans do. But the
arms are disproportionate. One is small and thin, the other is large and

02:29.240 --> 02:40.220
powerful. Right. Niven says he took that idea from studying the structures of
living creatures on Earth. In that case, I had the idea that I was following a

02:40.220 --> 02:54.300
progression with a protozoan, with an amoeba. You get radial symmetry inside and
out. Move up a goodly distance and you find starfishes with radial symmetry on

02:54.300 --> 03:06.280
the outside and bilateral symmetry on the inside. Move up a little further, you
find flatworms and worms of all stance. At the level of bilateral symmetry

03:06.280 --> 03:19.420
inside and out. Go as far as a human, you find bilateral symmetry on the outside
and no symmetry, well, half symmetrical on the inside. The lungs look

03:19.420 --> 03:31.560
symmetrical, the kidneys look symmetrical, the intestines look like somebody
dropped a plate of spaghetti. I tried to move on to the next step, bilaterally

03:31.560 --> 03:38.780
unsymmetrical on the outside. And I got the original Motie, which was the
engineer for them.

03:50.080 --> 03:58.220
The other ingenious idea Niven developed for the Moties is the way they construct
and use machines. They're highly skilled tool users, but they have no standard

03:58.220 --> 04:06.500
pre-manufactured machines, parts, or tools. They simply alter or reshape
whatever they find around them at the time to suit their needs. Niven says that

04:06.500 --> 04:17.360
particular idea just came to him. It seemed interesting and even logical. I was
just playing with ideas at that point, and that one seemed like a fun one. It

04:17.360 --> 04:31.660
also seemed likely enough, if you've got a critter with not much intelligence
except in the direction of tool making and tool altering, then why not? But the

04:31.660 --> 04:43.200
thing has to keep testing its ability or it will lose it. It might as well be
designing something every time it needs a specific machine. Besides the

04:43.200 --> 04:51.560
ingenuity Niven demonstrated in creating the Moties, he and Pournelle also weaved
some unexpected twists into the first contact theme. A reader interested in

04:51.560 --> 04:56.140
aliens, or more specifically in first contact, can't afford to overlook the Mote
in God's eye.

