06:29.040 --> 06:36.820
This is Daryl Lane. And to Bill Vernon. The so-called new wave in science
fiction, which began in the mid-60s, was simply a new way of writing traditional

06:36.820 --> 06:46.900
science fiction. There were changes, for instance, in... ...the modernization
was given more emphasis. ...sex and religion, that science fiction hadn't

06:46.900 --> 06:56.940
really... ...the new wave changed the stereotyped science fiction formulas
that... ...since the pulp days of the 20s, 30s, and 40s. Frederik Pohl, who's

06:56.940 --> 07:06.620
been an author, an editor, and an agent in the field of science fiction, has
something to say about that change. The new wave was an attempt, I guess, 15

07:06.620 --> 07:14.600
years ago or more, of a number of writers to break away from the traditional
kinds of fiction. In fact, most of them didn't want to call it science fiction

07:14.600 --> 07:26.180
anymore. They wanted to call it speculative fiction, or... And they were
interested, merely, in writing about the inner space, rather than... ...the

07:26.180 --> 07:38.240
second, really, a lot of them... ...in things like... ...and rock music and so
on. But... ...in the... ...rather bitter internal... ...stool that went on in

07:38.240 --> 07:45.420
science fiction, a lot of people take the science one way or the other. I
think... ...people... ... ...

07:52.660 --> 07:57.160
But we need to remember here that the New Wave wasn't really a planned and deliberate movement

07:57.160 --> 08:01.380
by a unified group of writers. One of the principal proponents of the New Wave,

08:01.800 --> 08:06.300
author Norman Spinrad, believes it was just a bunch of diverse writers doing their own thing.

08:07.220 --> 08:11.960
It was an old way, but there was never as a coherent philosophy in school of science fiction,

08:11.960 --> 08:16.460
but there was never a New Wave in the same sense. There were a lot of ways. There are a lot of

08:16.460 --> 08:20.840
different people doing a lot of different things. The people that were identified as the New Wave

08:20.840 --> 08:27.020
were very diverse. What I was actually writing is very different to what Tom Dish was writing,

08:27.260 --> 08:33.260
or Ballard, or Zelazny, or Delaney were also identified as New Wave writers. This stuff is

08:33.920 --> 08:39.060
much more than, you know, Zelazny and Delaney and myself and Ballard and Aldiss and Mike,

08:39.060 --> 08:50.040
but there were more differences between our work and the old stuff. There was more difference

08:50.040 --> 08:53.380
within the so-called New Wave than there was within the so-called old Wave.

08:54.240 --> 08:58.420
But Spinrad also thinks the New Wave was tightly connected to what was happening in society.

08:59.680 --> 09:04.180
Of course, this mirrored the cultural climate at the time. It mirrored what was happening politically,

09:04.180 --> 09:07.940
it mirrored what was happening in music, it mirrored what was happening in movies,

09:08.200 --> 09:12.440
it was a phenomenon that went through the western civilizations at home.

09:19.020 --> 09:24.080
There are those who say the New Wave is dead. Five-time Hugo winner Larry Niven says so,

09:24.160 --> 09:30.140
for instance, and offers a reason for his passing. The New Wave is a very persuasive thing,

09:30.730 --> 09:39.800
and very easy to use to justify bad stories. I think that's what killed it. Not the

09:40.700 --> 09:49.740
increased characterization and experiments with typography and story format are a bad thing

09:49.740 --> 09:56.600
in themselves, but it's so easy to use New Wave to justify a bad story. It was bound to go out.

10:02.700 --> 10:07.040
The influence of the New Wave is still around, though. It's left its mark on the field.

10:07.520 --> 10:10.860
Science fiction has been broadened, maybe enhanced somehow because of it.

10:11.200 --> 10:12.580
Frederik Pohl states it well.

10:13.640 --> 10:18.540
And the New Wave, if nothing else, taught a bunch of old dinosaurs like Asimov and

10:19.940 --> 10:25.180
Heinlein and me, that there were non-traditional ways of constructing a novel.

10:25.180 --> 10:29.460
See, most of us had grown up when science fiction was in the pulp magazine,

10:29.660 --> 10:33.340
and most of it was written according to some variant of a pulp formula.

10:34.460 --> 10:39.780
Well, it's necessary. I think the New Wave is responsible for teaching us that.

