12:13.920 --> 12:18.500
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane. The award-winning novel Ringworld is probably

12:18.500 --> 12:23.500
Larry Niven's finest work. The Ringworld is an immense ring, large enough to hold 3 million

12:23.500 --> 12:28.780
Earths, and with a thousand-mile high wall to hold in its atmosphere. It also has continents and oceans.

12:29.460 --> 12:32.080
The Ringworld contains trillions of inhabitants of different species,

12:32.560 --> 12:37.180
and derives energy from the sun at its center. Niven recalls where he obtained the idea for such

12:37.180 --> 12:45.800
a fantastic structure. I ran across the concept Dyson's sphere. Dyson, the mathematician, came up

12:45.800 --> 12:50.880
with the concept Dyson's shell, and he was misunderstood to some extent. So,

12:51.680 --> 12:58.800
presently, I ran across an article about Dyson's sphere. A picture that is a golf ball, 93 million

12:58.800 --> 13:05.840
miles in radius, with a sun at the center, and gravity generators all around the outside, so

13:05.840 --> 13:12.860
he would live on the inside, terraform it with oceans and soil and air.

13:13.420 --> 13:20.760
I ran across that and I didn't like it. I thought it could be improved, and I wound up with the Ringworld.

13:27.840 --> 13:32.280
Reader studied the science behind the Ringworld and wrote Niven about seeming inconsistencies in

13:32.280 --> 13:39.100
the design of the immense artifact. Column errors and elaborations because some of them don't really

13:39.100 --> 13:43.360
fit the errors. It's just something that hadn't gotten into the original book.

13:44.140 --> 13:48.940
One of the errors was spotted by some MIT students. It had to do with the instability of the Ringworld.

13:49.740 --> 13:56.440
I suspected the Ringworld was unstable, and I suspected you'd eat attitude jets. I was sure that

13:56.440 --> 14:01.960
the Ringworld was spinning fast enough to permit Bussard ramjets to be used as attitude jets,

14:02.060 --> 14:05.520
which means you don't have a fuel problem at all. You're burning the solar wind.

14:07.620 --> 14:13.320
But rapidly, some MIT people demonstrated that the Ringworld was unstable, and they were canning it

14:13.320 --> 14:19.260
in the halls at the next World Cup. The Ringworld is unstable. The Ringworld is unstable.

14:21.900 --> 14:27.980
It still took about seven years for anyone to figure out the exact numbers for the instability,

14:28.280 --> 14:34.560
and they are horrifying. The Ringworld, a major solar flare, would have the Ringworld

14:34.560 --> 14:41.480
grinding against its sun in five years. Well, I worked it in the plot. That was one

14:41.480 --> 14:48.160
elaboration or error. Even teenage readers analyzed his Ringworld with a critical scientific eye.

14:49.120 --> 14:55.200
A high school class in Florida got to work on the Ringworld, and their conclusion was that the

14:55.200 --> 15:00.860
Ringworld's worst problem is that all the top soil would wind up in the oceans in about 3,000 years.

15:01.500 --> 15:06.060
There are no earthquakes on the Ringworld. No mountain building forces.

15:13.060 --> 15:18.280
But in a sequel, Ringworld Engineers, Niven attempted to correct such deficiencies.

15:18.660 --> 15:21.840
He devised a way to answer the criticism of the Florida high schoolers.

15:23.900 --> 15:32.220
Okay, that's a tough one. I set up a spill pipe system that runs the bottom from the

15:32.220 --> 15:40.300
sea bottoms under the Ringworld and up over the edge of the Ringwall. That even allows you some

15:40.300 --> 15:47.640
some mind accumulation of useful metals.

15:57.840 --> 16:00.920
Fan response of that sort caused Ringworld engineers to be written,

16:01.360 --> 16:04.320
and although Niven once said he wouldn't write anymore in the Known Space series,

16:04.800 --> 16:08.020
the body of stories to which Ringworld belongs, he's not so sure anymore.

16:09.460 --> 16:17.060
I've given up saying that the Known Space series is dead. There's just no point in it.

16:17.160 --> 16:21.600
I've written five books worth of Known Space stories since I said that.

16:22.300 --> 16:23.460
More on Larry Niven tomorrow.

